06608nam a22008415i 9781787444201DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817874442017 a10.1515/97817874442012doi  a(DE-B1597)675051  a(OCoLC)1420507263  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a833/.91222300aKafka after Kafka :bDialogical Engagement with His Works from the Holocaust to Postmodernism /ced. by Iris Bruce, Mark H. Gelber.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2019] 1bCamden House, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b14 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in German Literature Linguistics and Culture ;v19500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Philosophical and Literary Hermeneutics after the Holocaust -- t1: Tradition of Loss: Werner Kraft on Franz Kafka -- t2: A Brave New Word: Hannah Arendt’s Postwar Reading of Kafka -- t3: Binding Words: Sarah Kofman, Maurice Blanchot, Franz Kafka, and the Holocaust -- t4: Kafka as the Exemplary Subject of Recent Dominant Critical Approaches -- tPart II. Kafka in Israeli Cultural Space -- t5: Kafka and Brod after the Trial and Judgments in Israel -- t6: “A Nightingale Whose Tongue Was Chopped Off”: The Melancholic Writing Machine in Ya’acov Shṭeinberg’s and Ḥezi Leskly’s Poetry, after Kafka -- t7: Exiles in Their Own Lands: Kafka and Sayed Kashua -- tPart III. Kafka from Modernism to Postmodernism -- t8: The Beetle and the Butterfly: Nabokov’s Lecture on Kafka’s The Metamorphosis -- t9: “When the Still Image Projected on the Screen Bursts into Movement”: Cinematic Space-Time in Kafka’s “A Country Doctor” -- t10: After the Animal: Kafka, Monstrosity, and the Graphic Novel -- t11: Kafkas after Kafka: Anglophone Poetry and the Image of Kafka -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNew essays providing an up-to-date picture of the engagement of artists, philosophers, and critics with Kafka's work.The topic of "Kafka after Kafka" is a fascinating one: the engagement of artists, philosophers, and critics in dialogical exchange with Kafka's works. The present collection of new essays highlights the engagement of lesser knownartists and commentators with Kafka, and represents those who are well known, such as Arendt, Blanchot, Nabokov, and Coetzee, from new perspectives. The eleven essays contained here represent the most recent scholarly engagements with this topic. An essay on major trends in current Kafka criticism provides background for several essays on novelists, philosophers, and critics whose relationship to Kafka is not very well known. A section devoted to Kafka from an Israeli perspective includes artists not commonly known in the US or Europe (Ya'acov Shteinberg, Hezi Leskly, Sayed Kashua), as well as an essay on the recent trial in Israel regarding the fate of Kafka's literary legacy. A final section addresses important contemporary approaches to Kafka in film studies, animal studies, the graphic novel, and in postmodern culture and counterculture. Contributors: Iris Bruce, Stanley Corngold, AmirEngel, Mark H. Gelber, Sander L. Gilman, Caroline Jessen, Tali Latowicki, Michael G. Levine, Ido Lewit, Vivian Liska, Alana Sobelman. Iris Bruce is Associate Professor of German at McMaster University. Mark H. Gelber is Senior Professor and Director of the Center for Austrian and German Studies at Ben-Gurion University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern History. 4aPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aArtists.  aContemporary perspectives.  aCritics.  aDialogical engagemen